      overview: "Adult epiglottitis is an underrecognized, life-threatening infection of the epiglottis and surrounding supraglottic structures. Unlike pediatric epiglottitis (which has decreased dramatically due to Hib vaccination), adult epiglottitis is increasing in incidence. It can rapidly progress to complete airway obstruction. The key prehospital intervention is early recognition, avoidance of airway manipulation, and rapid transport.",
      mechanism: "Bacterial infection (Haemophilus influenzae, Streptococcus, Staphylococcus) causes inflammation and edema of the epiglottis, aryepiglottic folds, and surrounding supraglottic tissue. The edematous epiglottis can obstruct the laryngeal inlet. Unlike children, adults have a larger airway diameter, so complete obstruction is less common but still life-threatening. Adult epiglottitis progresses over hours rather than the minutes seen in children.",
      clinicalRelevance: "Adult epiglottitis is often misdiagnosed as pharyngitis or croup. The triad of severe sore throat, odynophagia (painful swallowing), and muffled ('hot potato') voice should raise immediate suspicion. Paramedics should avoid oropharyngeal examination with a tongue depressor (can trigger laryngospasm) and prepare for a difficult airway.",
      signsSymptoms: "Severe sore throat (often described as the worst sore throat of their life), dysphagia and odynophagia (drooling because swallowing is too painful), muffled or 'hot potato' voice, stridor (late finding indicating significant obstruction), fever, tripod positioning (leaning forward with neck extended), and anxiety. Unlike children, adults may not have the classic 'sniffing' position.",
      assessment: "Assess for the triad: severe sore throat, drooling/dysphagia, and muffled voice. Assess respiratory status: stridor (ominous — indicates >50% airway obstruction), respiratory rate, SpO2, and work of breathing. Do NOT use a tongue depressor to examine the throat — this can trigger complete laryngospasm. Do NOT lay the patient supine — maintain upright positioning. Prepare for emergent airway management.",
      management: "Keep the patient calm and upright (anxiety increases oxygen demand). Supplemental oxygen (humidified if available — avoid blow-by that agitates the patient). Do NOT attempt blind nasotracheal or orotracheal intubation unless complete obstruction occurs (difficult airway — edematous supraglottic tissue). If complete obstruction: surgical cricothyrotomy (the obstruction is ABOVE the cricothyroid membrane). Nebulized epinephrine (racemic 2.25% 0.5 mL) may provide temporary improvement. Rapid transport to a facility with ENT/anesthesiology capability.",
      complications: "Complete airway obstruction and death, difficult/failed intubation (edematous tissue obscures landmarks), epiglottic abscess, mediastinitis, sepsis, and aspiration. Adult epiglottitis mortality is 1-3% with treatment but approaches 100% if airway obstruction occurs without intervention.",
