      faq: [
        { question: "How do you place posterior leads V7-V9?", answer: "Posterior leads are placed on the left posterior chest wall at the same horizontal level as V6: V7: left posterior axillary line. V8: tip of the left scapula (mid-scapular line). V9: left paraspinal border. Practical technique: after obtaining the standard 12-lead, move V4 to V7 position, V5 to V8, and V6 to V9. Run another ECG. Label it clearly as 'posterior leads.' ST elevation >0.5 mm in any posterior lead confirms posterior STEMI. Some monitors have a 'posterior leads' mode that labels them correctly." },
        { question: "Why are the changes in V1-V3 'reciprocal'?", answer: "Leads V1-V3 face the anterior wall of the heart. They are on the OPPOSITE side of the heart from the posterior wall. When the posterior wall has ST elevation (injury current), leads V1-V3 see the mirror image of this from the opposite direction — resulting in ST depression. Similarly, posterior Q waves (tissue death) appear as tall R waves in V1-V3. And posterior T wave inversions appear as upright tall T waves in V1-V3. This mirror-image concept is the key to recognizing posterior MI on a standard 12-lead: flip V1-V3 upside down, and you'll see classic STEMI findings." }
      ],
      keywords: ["posterior MI paramedic", "posterior STEMI recognition", "V7-V9 posterior leads", "reciprocal ST depression", "missed STEMI posterior wall"],
