      faq: [
        { question: "What causes rhabdomyolysis?", answer: "Traumatic: crush injuries, prolonged immobilization (falls with prolonged ground time), compartment syndrome, electrical injuries, and burns. Exertional: extreme exercise, heat stroke, seizures (prolonged muscle contraction), and excited delirium. Toxic: cocaine, amphetamines, statins, alcohol (especially with immobilization), and NMS/serotonin syndrome. Medical: hypokalemia, hypothyroidism, and inflammatory myopathies. The most common EMS-relevant causes are crush injuries, prolonged immobilization in elderly fall patients, exertional heat stroke, and stimulant drug use." },
        { question: "How does rhabdomyolysis cause kidney failure?", answer: "Myoglobin released from damaged muscle is freely filtered by the kidneys. In the renal tubules, myoglobin precipitates (especially in acidic, concentrated urine), causing: (1) Direct tubular obstruction — blocking urine flow. (2) Direct nephrotoxicity — myoglobin generates free radicals that damage tubular cells. (3) Renal vasoconstriction — myoglobin scavenges nitric oxide, reducing renal blood flow. Aggressive IV hydration prevents kidney failure by: diluting myoglobin concentration, maintaining high urine flow (flushing myoglobin through before it can precipitate), and maintaining renal perfusion." }
      ],
      keywords: ["rhabdomyolysis paramedic", "myoglobinuria management", "dark urine trauma", "crush injury kidney failure", "muscle breakdown treatment"],
      related: ["crush-injury-and-crush-syndrome", "hyperkalemia", "heat-stroke", "acute-kidney-injury"]
